<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Britain said it has received two Iranian requests for a meeting in Geneva to 
resolve the furor over author Salman Rushdie and his novel "The Satanic Verses" 
but that it will reject any such request until Tehran renounces violence over 
the book. Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe said there could be no justification 
for Iran's death threats against the author, even though the book is "deeply 
offensive" to Muslims. Iran denied proposing a meeting, saying that the 
overtures for conciliation came from Britain and the Rushdie remains subject to 
"divine offensive." Howe plans to meet in Vienna on Monday with Soviet Foreign 
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, who has indicated a willingness to mediate the 
dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
