</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL BASKETBALL PLAYOFFS; 
</P>
<P>
GIRLS' DIVISION V; 
</P>
<P>
LA JOLLA COUNTRY DAY WINS ON SCHOEPFLIN FREE THROWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LAURA PALMER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was only fitting that Isabel Schoepflin got the winning free throws in La 
Jolla Country Day's 49-47 victory over Calvin Christian in the Division V 
girls' basketball championships Thursday at the Sports Arena. 
</P>
<P>
Coach Jack Wigley said no one wanted the victory more than Schoepflin, who had 
played every minute the past two games. 
</P>
<P>
"She's got tremendous timing for a sophomore," Wigley said. 
</P>
<P>
Schoepflin, who started last year as a freshman, was a first-team all-league 
selection this season. 
</P>
<P>
The Torres (17-5) not only defended their division championship, they also got 
revenge on the Crusaders (23-2), who had defeated them twice this season. 
</P>
<P>
"I think we won it because we wanted to win it after they beat us twice," 
Schoepflin said. 
</P>
<P>
With less than a minute to play, Betsy Wilgenburg made a steal and drove 
downcourt for a layup to put Calvin Christian ahead, 47-46. Schoepflin was 
fouled with 35 seconds left and made one of two free throws to tie the score, 
47-47. Nine seconds later, Schoepflin was fouled again and this time made both 
free throws. 
</P>
<P>
Calvin Christian, which led most of the game, had a chance to win but missed 
two layups in the final 10 seconds. The Crusaders led throughout the first half 
but the Torres' Julie Corbo scored at the buzzer to tie the score, 22-22, at 
halftime. Calvin Christian's Betsy Wilgenburg scored at the third-quarter 
buzzer to tie the score again, 34-34. Schoepflin, who had only two points in 
the first half, led the Torres with 13 points. Nancy Dickerson and Robin 
Chatman each added 10 points. 
</P>
<P>
The Torres' goal was to stop Calvin Christian's 5-9 guard, Wilgenburg, who led 
her team with 19 points. 
</P>
<P>
"We went more man-to-man and tried to shut Betsy down," Wigley said. "She's 
tough to stop." 
</P>
</TEXT>
