<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An early-morning fire Thursday in two abandoned buildings, at the corner of 
Kettner Boulevard and Broadway in downtown San Diego, is believed to have been 
caused by transients, fire officials said. 
</P>
<P>
It took firefighters 15 minutes to bring the fire, which began in vacant 
one-story businesses, under control, said Larry Stewart, Fire Department public 
information officer. 
</P>
<P>
The Metro Arson Strike Team suspected that the fire was set by transients who 
frequent the building. Two transients, who returned to the scene and claimed 
they were sleeping inside the building when the fire broke out, were treated 
for smoke inhalation. 
</P>
<P>
There was no estimate of damages to the buildings, which are scheduled to be 
demolished, fire officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA030389-0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 25812 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 3, 1989, Friday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
